  <main>
  <div class="bg-white rounded-lg shadow p-8 space-y-6 mb-12">
    <h3 class="text-3xl font-semibold text-green-700 mb-4">What is Permaculture?</h3>
    <p class="text-lg text-gray-800">
      Permaculture is a holistic design system for creating sustainable human environments by mimicking natural ecosystems. It integrates principles of ecology, regenerative agriculture, and community resilience to develop systems that are self-sustaining and resource-efficient.
    </p>
    <p class="text-lg text-gray-800">
      Permaculture emphasizes the use of renewable resources, biodiversity, and ethical care for the earth, people, and future generations. Its practices include water management, soil restoration, companion planting, and energy-efficient living. By observing and working with nature, permaculture aims to harmonize human activity with the environment, fostering abundance and resilience in food production, shelter, and community systems. It’s a framework for regenerative and sustainable living.
    </p>
    <h4 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-green-700 mt-6">How is Permaculture Different from Regular Agriculture?</h4>
    <ul class="space-y-4 text-lg text-gray-800">
      <li><strong>Design Philosophy:</strong> <span class="text-green-700">🌿 Permaculture: Focuses on designing ecosystems that mimic natural processes, aiming for long-term sustainability and self-regeneration.</span> <span class="text-gray-600">🚜 Traditional Agriculture: Often prioritizes maximizing short-term yields, sometimes at the expense of soil health and ecosystem balance.</span></li>
      <li><strong>Diversity vs. Monoculture:</strong> <span class="text-green-700">🌼 Permaculture: Promotes biodiversity through polycultures and companion planting to create resilient ecosystems.</span> <span class="text-gray-600">🌾 Traditional Agriculture: Relies heavily on monocultures, which can lead to pest outbreaks, soil depletion, and dependency on chemical inputs.</span></li>
      <li><strong>Soil Health:</strong> <span class="text-green-700">🌱 Permaculture: Builds soil health through practices like composting, mulching, and minimal tilling.</span> <span class="text-gray-600">🔄 Traditional Agriculture: Often depletes soil nutrients through intensive tillage and chemical fertilizers, leading to erosion and degradation.</span></li>
      <li><strong>Energy Use:</strong> <span class="text-green-700">☀️ Permaculture: Utilizes renewable energy sources and passive energy designs.</span> <span class="text-gray-600">⛽ Traditional Agriculture: Often depends on fossil fuels for machinery, irrigation, and synthetic inputs.</span></li>
      <li><strong>Water Management:</strong> <span class="text-green-700">💧 Permaculture: Implements water-conserving techniques such as swales, rainwater harvesting, and contour planting.</span> <span class="text-gray-600">🚰 Traditional Agriculture: Frequently relies on large-scale irrigation systems, which can lead to water wastage and depletion of local water sources.</span></li>
      <li><strong>Ethics and Sustainability:</strong> <span class="text-green-700">🌍 Permaculture: Operates on ethical principles: care for the earth, care for people, and fair share of resources.</span> <span class="text-gray-600">📈 Traditional Agriculture: Typically driven by economic priorities, sometimes overlooking environmental and social impacts.</span></li>
      <li><strong>Inputs and Waste:</strong> <span class="text-green-700">♻️ Permaculture: Seeks to minimize external inputs by recycling nutrients and resources within the system.</span> <span class="text-gray-600">🚮 Traditional Agriculture: Often depends on synthetic fertilizers, pesticides, and herbicides, which can create waste and pollution.</span></li>
    </ul>
    <p class="text-lg text-gray-800">
      In essence, permaculture works with nature to create regenerative systems, while traditional agriculture often imposes human-centered systems on the land, which can degrade natural resources over time.
    </p>
  </div>

  <!-- Why Permaculture Matters Section -->
  <div class="bg-white rounded-lg shadow p-8 space-y-6 mb-12">
    <h3 class="text-3xl font-semibold text-green-700 mb-4">Why Permaculture Matters</h3>
    <p class="text-lg text-gray-800">
      Permaculture is a holistic design system that focuses on sustainable living and regenerative land use. It integrates principles of ecology, agriculture, and community building to create systems that are productive, resilient, and self-sustaining.
    </p>

    <h4 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-green-700 mt-6">Key Reasons Why Permaculture Matters</h4>
    <ul class="space-y-4 text-lg text-gray-800">
      <li><strong>Sustainability:</strong> <span class="text-green-700">🌿 Core Principle: Permaculture creates systems that sustain themselves with minimal external input.</span> <span class="text-gray-600">Why It Matters: It reduces our reliance on fossil fuels and non-renewable resources while promoting renewable energy, natural building techniques, and water conservation practices.</span></li>
      <li><strong>Soil Regeneration:</strong> <span class="text-green-700">🌱 Core Principle: Permaculture prioritizes soil health, the foundation of all life on Earth.</span> <span class="text-gray-600">Why It Matters: Regenerative practices prevent erosion, restore degraded lands, and increase soil fertility through natural methods like composting, mulching, and crop rotation.</span></li>
      <li><strong>Biodiversity:</strong> <span class="text-green-700">🌼 Core Principle: By mimicking natural ecosystems, permaculture promotes a diverse range of plants, animals, and microorganisms.</span> <span class="text-gray-600">Why It Matters: Resilient ecosystems are less vulnerable to disease, pests, and environmental stresses. Biodiversity supports pollinators and wildlife, contributing to a balanced and thriving environment.</span></li>
      <li><strong>Food Security:</strong> <span class="text-green-700">🍎 Core Principle: Permaculture designs small-scale, efficient food systems that provide abundant food in limited spaces.</span> <span class="text-gray-600">Why It Matters: It reduces our dependency on industrial agriculture, which often harms the environment. Local food production reduces transportation-related emissions and provides fresh, nutrient-rich food.</span></li>
      <li><strong>Water Conservation & Management:</strong> <span class="text-green-700">💧 Core Principle: Permaculture emphasizes the efficient capture, storage, and use of water.</span> <span class="text-gray-600">Why It Matters: Techniques like swales, rainwater harvesting, and greywater recycling reduce water waste and improve water retention in the landscape, helping to combat drought and desertification.</span></li>
      <li><strong>Climate Change Mitigation:</strong> <span class="text-green-700">🌍 Core Principle: Permaculture sequesters carbon through practices such as soil health improvement, tree planting, and regenerative agriculture.</span> <span class="text-gray-600">Why It Matters: It reduces greenhouse gas emissions from industrial farming and deforestation, while creating resilient systems that can adapt to changing climate conditions.</span></li>
      <li><strong>Community Building:</strong> <span class="text-green-700">👥 Core Principle: Permaculture fosters collaboration, knowledge-sharing, and community self-reliance.</span> <span class="text-gray-600">Why It Matters: It strengthens local economies, promotes ethical decision-making, and encourages equitable resource sharing.</span></li>
      <li><strong>Cost-Effective Living:</strong> <span class="text-green-700">💰 Core Principle: Efficient design reduces waste and consumption of resources.</span> <span class="text-gray-600">Why It Matters: By producing food, energy, and resources locally, permaculture lowers living expenses. It also creates opportunities for bartering and trading within communities.</span></li>
      <li><strong>Connection to Nature:</strong> <span class="text-green-700">🌳 Core Principle: Permaculture encourages a deeper understanding and respect for natural processes.</span> <span class="text-gray-600">Why It Matters: It enhances our mental and physical well-being, encourages outdoor activities, and inspires mindfulness. A stronger connection to nature fosters a sense of stewardship for the Earth.</span></li>
      <li><strong>Global Impact:</strong> <span class="text-green-700">🌏 Core Principle: Small, localized actions can collectively have a significant impact on global sustainability.</span> <span class="text-gray-600">Why It Matters: Permaculture empowers individuals and communities to address environmental challenges and demonstrates scalable solutions for global issues like hunger, water scarcity, and habitat loss.</span></li>
    </ul>
  </div>
